those questions and more. Using data from six movement organizations—including a coalition that organized a 104-day protest in Phoenix in 2010 and another that helped restore voting rights to the formerly incarcerated in Virginia—Hahrie Han, Elizabeth McKenna, and Michelle Oyakawa show that the power of successful movements most often is rooted in their ability to act as “prisms of the people,” turning participation into political power just as prisms transform white light into rainbows. Understanding the organizational design choices that shape the people, their leaders, and their strategies can help us understand how grassroots groups achieve their goals. Linking strong scholarship to a deep understanding of the needs and outlook of activists, Prisms of the People is the perfect book for our moment—for understanding what’s happening and propelling it forward.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aOrganizational sociology. 0aPolitical leadershipzUnited States. 0aPolitical sciencexDecision making. 0aPower (Social sciences)zUnited States. 0aSocial movementszUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aSocial movementszUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  agrassroots organizing, collective action, political movements, social change, politics, democracy, 2016 election, poverty, justice, inequity, inequality, constituents, voters, nonfiction, power, marginalized, coalition, protests, voting rights, phoenix, virginia, felons, arizona, participation, activism, leadership, decision making, sociology, organizations.1 aMcKenna, Elizabeth, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aOyakawa, Michelle, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package: